{"title_page": "T.T. the Bear's Place", "text_new": "[[File:TTs.jpg|thumb|TTs]]\n\n'''T.T. the Bear's Place''' (often referred to as '''T.T. the Bear's''' or, simply, '''TT's''') was a live music venue in [[Central_Square,_Cambridge|Central Square]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] that operated from 1984 until July 25, 2015.\n\n== History ==\nT.T. the Bear's began in 1973, opened by New Hampshire native, Bonney Bouley, and her boyfriend at the time, Miles Cares, as something of a [[dive bar]], originally located on the corner of Pearl and Green Streets, around the corner from its final location. They closed it briefly in 1978, only to reopen at a new location, 10 Brookline Street, in Central Square, in 1980, originally as a restaurant; due to back taxes, Ms. Bouley filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy, then changed the format to a full-time music club in 1984.<ref>http://artery.wbur.org/2015/07/22/t-t-the-bears</ref> T.T.'s helped define Central Square, along with [[The Middle East (nightclub)|The Middle East]] and, across the street, [[Manray]]. \n\nTT's had a capacity of only 300 patrons, which contributed to its intimacy between performer and audience. The club's name originated from the need to be unique, to not have a name like any other establishment; the owners considered their own names, Miles & Bonney's; eventually they decided to name it after their pet \"Teddy Bear\"-style hamster, who was nicknamed Tough Teddy, hence they settled on T.T. the Bear's Place. <ref name=\"GlobeNight\">https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/07/16/after-years-cambridge-legendary-club-bear-place-calls-night/tw4iusGlhMTWVobUGo7laK/story.html</ref> <ref name=\"wickedlocal\">http://cambridge.wickedlocal.com/article/20150519/NEWS/150516312</ref> \n\nFor 42 years, TT's was a prominent venue within the Boston music scene; it played host to both national touring acts and local bands, with 250 nights each year featuring live music.<ref>http://www.vanyaland.com/2015/05/15/after-40-years-of-rock-and-roll-t-t-the-bears-place-will-reportedly-close-this-summer/</ref>  TT's celebrated its 40th anniversary in 2013.  Bonney Bouley has been the owner for the entire 42-year run.<ref name=\"GlobeNight\" /> \n\nIn December 2014, the building was purchased by Joseph and Nabil Sater, owners of the adjacent [[The Middle East (nightclub)|Middle East]] restaurant and music venue complex. In early 2015, the owners announced that there was to be a substantial rent increase, and a lease of five years, with an option for another five years. Ms. Bouley did not agree to the terms (she considered the rent high and the lease to be \"short-term\") and, without the new lease, the club could not be successfully sold to a new owner. Bouley decided in May 2015 that the club would close.<ref>http://www.vanyaland.com/2015/05/18/t-t-the-bears-place-owner-bonney-bouley-announces-final-night-for-cambridge-rock-club/</ref><ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/05/19/owner-makes-official-cambridge-club-bear-place-closing-july/2ndTlrcvmPFVZlNGWSoh3O/story.html</ref> \n\nMany bands paid tribute to TT's during its final month.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/07/16/boston-artists-share-bear-place-stories/PfRRrgGrXGPB3fTFqS0zAL/story.html?p1=Article_Related_Box_Article</ref><ref>http://www.bostonherald.com/entertainment/music/guestlisted/2015/07/last_best_show_bosstones_help_say_goodbye_to_legendary_rock</ref><ref>http://artery.wbur.org/2015/07/24/tt-the-bears-closes</ref> TT's last open night was Saturday, July 25, 2015, and the final scheduled bands on stage were O-Positive followed by [[Scruffy The Cat]], with Dave Minehan of [[The Neighborhoods]] sitting in on vocals and guitar for the late Charlie Chesterman. Scruffy was personally chosen by Ms. Bouley to be the closing band as she had a long relationship with the band, who played her venue multiple times per year in the 80's when she was getting started.<ref name=\"GlobeFinale\">https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/07/26/bear-finale-suitably-scruffy-occasion/C5cXOx8i3qUVUHQBF5wYZL/story.html?s_campaign=bostonglobe%3Asocialflow%3Atwitter</ref><ref>http://www.ttthebears.com/public/calendar.php</ref>\n\nBonney Bouley spoke at the finale: \u201cThe talent that is in this town and comes through this town is unbelievable. . . . It's been a wonderful journey and I hope to see you down the road.\"  A choked-up Bouley added that she hoped the club \u201cwon't go all corporate now.\u201d Asked what she will do next, Bouley, who resides in [[Dorchester, MA]], said: \u201cI'm going to take some time off to breathe.\" <ref name=\"GlobeFinale\" /> After July 15, 2015, the official Twitter page heading changed to \"That's all, folks! Thank you for the past 42 years\". \n\nThe new building owner, Mr. Sater, has stated that he would like the venue to remain as a home to some sort of nightlife.<ref name=\"wickedlocal\" /> On March 31, 2017, the venue reopened as a completely renovated live music venue called Sonia, now part of [[The Middle East (nightclub)|The Middle East]] complex.\n\n== Notable musical performances ==\nTT's has hosted such well-known [[Boston]] and national acts, examples being:\n*[[The Push Kings]]\n*[[Pixies (band)|Pixies]]\n*[[Mighty Mighty Bosstones]]\n*[[Jane's Addiction]]\n*[[The Lemonheads|Lemonheads]]\n*[[Dropkick Murphys]]\n*[[Tommy Stinson]] of [[The Replacements (band)|The Replacements]]\n*[[Mike Watt]]\n*[[Brian Jonestown Massacre]]\n*[[Arcade Fire]]\n*[[Dinosaur Jr.]]\n*[[Scruffy The Cat|Scruffy the Cat]]\n*[[Blake Babies]]\n*[[Mission of Burma]]\n*[[The Shins]]\n*[[O-Positive]]\n*[[Letters To Cleo]]\n*[[Gregory and the Hawk]]\n*[[Til Tuesday]]\n*[[The Dogmatics]]\n*[[The Neighborhoods]]\n*[[Mary Lou Lord]]\n*[[Peter Wolf]] of [[J Geils Band]]\n*[[Bikini Kill]]\n*[[Lyres (band)]]\n*[[Rivers Cuomo]] of [[Weezer]]\n*[[Tanya Donelly]]\n*[[Nelly Furtado]]\n*[[Indigo Girls]]\n*[[The Outlets]]\n*[[Rods and Cones]]\n*[[Willie Alexander]]\n*[[The Fools]]\n*[[The Smashing Pumpkins|Smashing Pumpkins]]\n*[[Sublime (band)|Sublime]]\n\nTT's hosted Boston's [[Rock 'n' Roll Rumble]] competition from 2011 until 2015.\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2009 Best Music Venue, small ([[Boston (magazine)|Boston Magazine]]) <ref>http://www.bostonmagazine.com/best-of-boston/2009/award/music-venue/small/</ref>\n*2008 Best Live Music Venue, small (Boston Magazine)<ref>http://www.bostonmagazine.com/best-of-boston/2008/t-t-the-bears-place-3/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://twitter.com/ttthebears Official Twitter Page]\n\n{{Coord|42|21|48.6|N|71|6|5.9|W|type:landmark_region:US_dim:44|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Nightclubs in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:TTs.jpg|thumb|TTs]]\n\n'''T.T. the Bear's Place''' (often referred to as '''T.T. the Bear's''' or, simply, '''TT's''') was a live music venue in [[Central_Square,_Cambridge|Central Square]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]] that operated from 1984 until July 25, 2015.\n\n== History ==\nT.T. the Bear's began in 1973, opened by New Hampshire native, Bonney Bouley, and her boyfriend at the time, Miles Cares, as something of a [[dive bar]], originally located on the corner of Pearl and Green Streets, around the corner from its final location. They closed it briefly in 1978, only to reopen at a new location, 10 Brookline Street, in Central Square, in 1980, originally as a restaurant; due to back taxes, Ms. Bouley filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy, then changed the format to a full-time music club in 1984.<ref>http://artery.wbur.org/2015/07/22/t-t-the-bears</ref> T.T.'s helped define Central Square, along with [[The Middle East (nightclub)|The Middle East]] and, across the street, [[Manray]]. \n\nTT's had a capacity of only 300 patrons, which contributed to its intimacy between performer and audience. The club's name originated from the need to be unique, to not have a name like any other establishment; the owners considered their own names, Miles & Bonney's; eventually they decided to name it after their pet \"Teddy Bear\"-style hamster, who was nicknamed Tough Teddy, hence they settled on T.T. the Bear's Place. <ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/07/16/after-years-cambridge-legendary-club-bear-place-calls-night/tw4iusGlhMTWVobUGo7laK/story.html</ref> <ref>http://cambridge.wickedlocal.com/article/20150519/NEWS/150516312</ref> \n\nFor 42 years, TT's was a prominent venue within the Boston music scene; it played host to both national touring acts and local bands, with 250 nights each year featuring live music.<ref>http://www.vanyaland.com/2015/05/15/after-40-years-of-rock-and-roll-t-t-the-bears-place-will-reportedly-close-this-summer/</ref>  TT's celebrated its 40th anniversary in 2013.  Bonney Bouley has been the owner for the entire 42-year run.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/07/16/after-years-cambridge-legendary-club-bear-place-calls-night/tw4iusGlhMTWVobUGo7laK/story.html</ref> \n\nIn December 2014, the building was purchased by Joseph and Nabil Sater, owners of the adjacent [[The Middle East (nightclub)|Middle East]] restaurant and music venue complex. In early 2015, the owners announced that there was to be a substantial rent increase, and a lease of five years, with an option for another five years. Ms. Bouley did not agree to the terms (she considered the rent high and the lease to be \"short-term\") and, without the new lease, the club could not be successfully sold to a new owner. Bouley decided in May 2015 that the club would close.<ref>http://www.vanyaland.com/2015/05/18/t-t-the-bears-place-owner-bonney-bouley-announces-final-night-for-cambridge-rock-club/</ref><ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/05/19/owner-makes-official-cambridge-club-bear-place-closing-july/2ndTlrcvmPFVZlNGWSoh3O/story.html</ref> \n\nMany bands paid tribute to TT's during its final month.<ref>https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/07/16/boston-artists-share-bear-place-stories/PfRRrgGrXGPB3